[1] Cholera, Dysentery - Tanzania (Dar es Salaam, Zanzibar)
Date: Mon, 13 Nov 2006
From: Brent Barrett <salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
Source: IRIN News [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/fdc2a768e46719ee92358bc431599b02.htm>

A cholera outbreak in Tanzania's commercial capital, Dar es Salaam, has
killed 5 people and affected 820 others, mostly women and children, who
have been hospitalized in the last few weeks, heath officials said on Mon,
13 Nov 2006.
"We call upon the public to observe health precautions by keeping their
environment clean, boiling drinking water and making use of toilets," Tatu
Mwaruka, a health officer in the city's Ilala Municipality, said. Ilala is
one of the districts forming the Dar es Salaam region with Kinondoni and
Temeke. All combine to make the city of Dar es Salaam.
Mwaruka said the outbreak was worse in the suburbs because of the public's
"reluctance to observe hygiene".
Health officials in Tanzania's semi-autonomous island of Zanzibar have also
recorded the hospitalization of least 16 people following an outbreak of
dysentery and diarrhea in Stone Town, capital of the island.
"We have cases of diarrhea and dysentery, but no cases of cholera and
deaths," Omar Suleiman, the director of information policy in Zanzibar's
Ministry of Health and Social Welfare, said on Mon, 13 Nov 2006.
In Aug 2006, health officials in Zanzibar reported that at least 454
children had been admitted to the main Mnazi-Mmoja Hospital, suffering from
severe dysentery and diarrhea.
Cholera and diarrhea outbreaks started in Mar 2006, resurfaced in late May
and June 2006 and again in July and August 2006 in most areas of the
Zanzibar Municipality and Pemba Island.
--
Brent Barrett
Indianapolis, IN
<salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
[A map of Tanzania showing the eastern coast capital of Dar es Salaam and
the islands of Zanzibar just off the northeast part of the mainland can be
found at: <http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/tanzania.pdf>
ProMED thanks Brent Barrett for this and the following postings. - Mod.LL]
