[3] Cholera - Uganda (Arua)
Date: Mon, 13 Nov 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and, The Monitor [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200611130386.html>

The soaring cholera prevalence in Arua has claimed lives of 7 residents and
left 176 others hospitalized, health officials and political leaders have said.
Ms Norah Fuathum, the town health inspector, on Fri, 11 Nov 2006 said the
epidemic had mostly ravaged River Oli Division in the
municipality. According to the up-dated health bulletin, 130 dwellers in
Oli had contracted cholera since the epidemic re-emerged in the urban
neighborhood on 12 Jul 2006.
River Oli Division is the most populated area of Arua town with inadequate
sanitation facilities and harboring mainly people with modest means.
"The continued prevalence of cholera means that people are still eating
contaminated food and I cannot understand why," Mr Charles Asiki, the
municipality mayor said.
According to the statistical break down from Oli Health Centre where all
cholera patients are being treated, only 3 cases of the disease were
registered from the urban Arua Hill division. Daily Monitor has learnt
that in Ayivu County, 48 cases of the epidemic have been reported from the
sub-counties of Dadamu, Oluko, Pajulu and Manibe over the last 4 months.
--
